Dr. Craig A. Harper, who is a professor in the Forestry, Wildlife and Fisheries Department at the University of Tennessee, spoke at the Morganton hearing in opposition. Dr. Harper is nationally recognized in quality deer management and has published many papers on such. Dr. Harper stated that there is no biological reason to try to establish one common deer season across the diverse state of NC. In fact there are many valid reasons to not have a common season statewide. I have attached a copy of an open letter from Dr. Harper on this issue. The deer population, weather, people, food sources, growing season, etc in the mountains, the piedmont and coastal plains are all considerably different. One size does not fit all and makes no biological sense. The Commission's deer density map on their own website supports our claim.  The same is true for the Commission's turkey season proposed changes. It is so glaringly apparent that these proposed changes are so ! seriously flawed that virtually everyone at these hearing, including the NCWRC biologist staff, understand it.


In the July, 2006 minutes of the Deer Committee meeting of the NCWRC, the minutes state that "In fact, discussion during the Deer Committee revealed that there is more support for decreasing the length of the all-lawful-weapons season in the Central Deer Season area" instead of these proposed increases in the season. In a later meeting of the Deer Committee in April, 2007 a hunter survey by the NCWRC with 5,005 hunter responses was presented to the committee. In these meeting minutes the "Committee felt that it would not be prudent to increase the length of the all-lawful-weapons season in any season area..."  And "Comments were made as to why this issue is being revisited again, and concerns were raised that our staff were being asked to evaluate and possibly propose a regulation proposal for which there is little to no support for at the field level." We are at a loss to understand why the Commissioners are trying to shove these changes th! rough when no staff biologists support it. Where are the studies and surveys that support their positions? Yet the NCWRC is still proposing to make these hunting regulation changes.  The Commission is not listening to the proven science of wildlife biology from their own biologists, outside biologists nor to the hunters of North Carolina. If the Commissioners ignore the science of wildlife biology our wildlife and hunting will suffer greatly.


There are many other significant detriments of this extended deer gun season if passed, such as bear hunters (who primarily use dogs) and deer hunters being in the woods at the same time and bird hunters effectively getting reduced hunting. The bear/deer issue in particular will create conflicts and animosity again as it did years ago when the seasons overlapped.


This is a very serious issue and will damage the fragile deer and turkey population in the central and western parts of our state where some hunters have just started quality deer management practices to improve the numbers and quality of deer. We don't have hunters from other states traveling to NC to hunt deer like the Midwest and other states. Why? Because our deer herds are not in good shape and don't produce many big, mature bucks.


The majority of NC hunters oppose this seriously flawed proposal. If the Wildlife Commission wants to promote wildlife in NC then they should propose changes to encourage and promote quality wildlife management programs that work. I hope you will join us in opposing these damaging hunting regulation proposals and will work to see they are NOT passed by the NCWRC.


Respectfully,

Brian Heath



