Comment: Dear Governor Perdue, My wife and I write on behalf of our son, Markus A. Lubans. As a 21 year old adult recipient of the Community Alternative Program (CAP) benefits in Durham County, he is caught in a bureaucratic dilemma. We are hoping that with the new legislative year and a new state administration, you may be able to do what is right for Markus and other adults with special needs caught in a similar circumstance. Early last year Markus moved out on his own, with a roommate, into a townhouse administered by the Durham County Community Living Program (DCCLP). This is a wonderful opportunity for Markus to develop and practice independent living skills and to be all he can be as a contributing member of our society. Impeding his progress is something called a CAP/ NC Medicaid mandated “spend down.” It is also known in Medicaid circles as the “deductible” and as the notorious, “242.” This latter number refers to the outdated financial base used in calculating Markus’ income. The “242” has not been adjusted for inflation and the cost of living since the early 1990s! As you may know, when someone like Markus receives his monthly Social Security check for $1017.00 he has to return to NC Medicaid over $750 dollars (each month) for the spend down. This leaves him with around $300.00 for rent he owes to DCCLP ($305.00) and nothing for food, clothing and transportation. On top of this is the NC Medicaid mandate that any money he earns through employment is added dollar for dollar to the spend down. So, if he earns $30.00 from his part time work at Duke School Library, he needs to hand it over to Medicaid. We have consulted with several Durham County officials, including Mr. Sammy Haithcock, the head of Durham Social Services, and attorneys about the logic, fairness and practicality of this sort of enforced poverty. They all tell us that, while unfair – even “stupid”, as one official terms it - it is the rule and DSS cannot deviate from it. We have sought a waiver for the spend down. This waiver is available to some Social Security recipients who receive CAP services. Again, a technicality: Because Markus’ gets SSA and has never received SSI, he is not qualified for the waiver, even if his circumstances are now identical to those people with the waiver! We are told that some waiver recipients, currently receiving SSA, qualify for the waiver because at some point in their lives they received SSI, even if for only a month! Here is what we think is fair: The Rule of 242 needs to be adjusted for all in its scope so that Markus can afford his rent, food and clothing which he could afford with his own Social Security benefit if it were left whole. And, any money Markus earns through work should be taxed at a normal rate, just like the rest of us. Some people tells us “Solve this mess, give up CAP.” Well, we are very grateful recipients of the CAP services Markus receives – they are essential to his living as a positive citizen. If you have questions, please do not hesitate to give us a call or send us an e-mail. Please let us know if there are other people we should contact to help Markus. Thank you, John Lubans, Jr. & Sheryl Anspaugh 2507 Sevier Street Durham, NC 27705 Phone 919 493 4979 E-mail: Lubans1@nc.rr.com

