Subject: Ramsey Street Alternative High School, Cumberland County

Comment: Please pass this forward to all those who care To all that this may concern, Ramsey Street Alternative High School, “A Positive Alternative;” I have been trying to understand what this phrase means and how it is translated within the school. So far, I have been unsuccessful. Ramsey Street Alternative High School is supposed to be an alternative for those students who could not function in a normal school setting. “Our MISSION is to provide at-risk students with opportunities to acquire academic and behavioral skills that will lead to a successful return to their regular schools and reach the goal of high school graduation.” In this statement listed on the schools website, http://www.rshs.ccs.k12.nc.us/, the key point here is behavioral skills; I have worked at the school since the beginning of the 2008-2009 school year and have yet to see any evidence of the students acquiring behavioral skills that will lead them back to their home schools. I was under the assumption that this school offered some sort of rehabilitation to the students, otherwise how would the student gain the skills necessary to return to their home schools. I thought that perhaps the students would be offered classes in such things as anger management or maybe social skill building, but instead they are offered classes like career management; what exactly does that mean to a Ramsey student? “The VISION at Ramsey Street High School is to foster a safe and positive learning environment which recognizes the importance of varying abilities, learning styles, diverse cultures, parental involvement and the importance of increasing student achievement.” http://www.rshs.ccs.k12.nc.us/ The students upon entering school, walk through a metal detector, pull out their pockets, raise their pant legs to see their socks, hand over all of their belongings to be hand checked, and get scanned by the metal detecting wand. I am certain that after this afternoon ritual all should feel safe, that is until you see students with cell phones and mp3 players that they were just searched for and found not to have. The students are not physically searched so it is impossible to know exactly what students have hidden under the folds of their clothes or in places that adults would not want to venture, so let’s hope that no one gets the bright idea to make a weapon out of plastic. A positive environment means to me a place that a student wants to come to, a place that is safe and inviting, an environment that allows students with varying abilities and learning styles to gain an education that is their right to have as an American. Most students are greeted at the door by being bullied or antagonized by adults. Students have been turned away from school and told to go home because their socks are too short, or they forgot to bring notebook paper. These children should never be turned away from school, for some this is their last chance before juvenile detention. Parental involvement at Ramsey high is stressed so much that you think students could not function at school without a parent or guardian. For some students they are not allowed to come to school without one, these parents or guardians are called shadows. Some shadows are more disruptive in the classroom then the student. I watched parental involvement once, it consisted of a parent yanking on their child’s hair while slapping them in the back of the head and cursing them, meanwhile no one steps in to aid the student. Is this what parental involvement really means? It is important to raise student achievement, but when a student understands that no matter what they do will still afford them at least a 65 for a grade, there is not much incentive for them to try. If the county wide policy is to never give a student less than a 65, then why not change the grading scale all together. Do we not have the power to do this; is this school system not the property of the community? There are so many things at Ramsey that need to be fixed; the school is being run for the benefit of the few while the many suffer every day. Class sizes are so out of control that students cannot learn and teachers cannot teach. There are classrooms with 2, 3, or 4 different class levels happening at the same time. Classes can get filled with over 30 students when the classes are not supposed to be bigger than 15. These students are considered by some to be the worst of the worst. Students with gang affiliations are put in classes with rival gang members, while the teacher is supposed to maintain control. Students curse teachers and walk out of class when they feel it necessary; other students get into slapping and cursing fests with another. If this happens in a teacher’s room then they are accused of having bad classroom management. Ramsey Street is supposed to be a reflection of other schools in the county so that when a student comes to the school they can pick up on all of the classes that their home school offered them. This is a situation that Ramsey cannot handle. The school is on a 3 x 3 block schedule instead of a 4 x 4 schedule like the rest of the county. Students who remain at Ramsey for an entire year are already losing 2 credits, and this situation is worse for anyone coming from Terry Sanford High School which is still on a 7 period schedule. So where did that 90 minutes go? Ramsey High School has to share a school with Ramsey Middle. This causes early hours for the middle school and very late hours for the high school. Are the students who attend these schools not important enough to the community to have their own schools with the same hours as the rest of the county? I watched the mistreatment of both teachers and students on a regular basis knowing that no matter whom I told, it just did not matter and nothing would change. These students deserve better from their community. Ramsey Street Alternative High School has become a glorified day care center for bad children and the teachers have become babysitters. I was convinced to take my grievances to a higher authority and was told that someone would come and investigate what was happening at Ramsey. What these students received was an appointment of someone to the board of education who would be in charge of all of the counties alternative programs. We do not need someone to convince parents and community members that having an alternative program is necessary. We need someone to convince the students and their guardians that coming to school at Ramsey will afford them an education. We need someone who will fix all of the things that went wrong at Ramsey Street Alternative High School. Please, do not take my word for what is happening at Ramsey, see for yourself, ask students, teachers, parents and community members who are directly involved with the school about what is going on there. If Ramsey Street Alternative High School is supposed to be the best program in the state then I would hate to see what is happening in the other alternative schools. I wanted to work with students at Ramsey because I grew up in similar situations to a lot of these students. I grew up in the county projects in Baltimore, was homeless, lived in foster homes and barely graduated from high school. I joined the military, was injured on a jump and finally entered college while in my 30’s. Not only did I graduate in 3 years, but I graduated with two degrees and graduated Magna Cum Laude from a local University. I chose to teach because I taught when I was in the military, I worked with teenagers on an everyday basis and it seemed a logical thing to do. I have a lot to learn about teaching but I also have a lot of experience to offer my students. I was told that because I am a first year teacher and I have not taught before, nor have I worked with teenagers that I do not understand or know what I am doing when it comes to the types of students that go to Ramsey High. I was also told that because I am a teacher I will come to work early, stay late and do anything I am told to do and I am expected to obey, if there is a conflict with my life outside of school then I am required to bring in documentation showing conflict and then I may be able to work something out. When a first year teacher is willing to resign their position to change careers in the middle of the school year, something is very wrong. I wanted to be part of the solution, but when it became clear that-that would not happen, I had to leave because I no longer wanted to be part of the problem. Someone needs to be the voice for these children and I hope that the community will step in and become that voice so that our students and their families will regain the confidence in our school system that was once there. I take this stand at what could be great risk to me and my family because someone needs to speak for those who cannot speak for themselves. Who am I but a parent of students in our school system, a teacher to our students, and a member of our community. Sincerely yours, Kimberli Jones Former Visual Arts and Art History Teacher at Ramsey Street Alternative High School

